[normal]How
[normal] will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roads” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road 
[normal]              
[normal]users, whilst also improving the environment?
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]It is difficult not to see a contradiction within this question: policies as such improve nothing
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]until
[normal] they have been put into place.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Meanwhile, environmental improvement, for many people, road
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]users
[normal] or not, could be seen to involve reduction of 
[normal]road traffic that
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]produces harmful emissions,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]plus
[normal] greater positive encouragement to non-motorists - not just cyclists and pedestrians using the
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]road
[normal] itself (where they have permission to do so), but those of all types trying to cross one of the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]defined
[normal] "strategic" roads.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Over and above all these considerations, NECTAR considers that the effective and lasting
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]enhancement
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]of 
[normal]safety[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]for all road users should always be a fundamental, indeed an automatic,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]required
[normal] output.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
