[normal] 
[normal]How does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]modes
[normal]?
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]It depends where you look, and (often) on which 'other' transport modes are being planned for.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]One of the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]strikingly honest points to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]emerge from the recen
[normal]t launch of the NECC/IPPR report
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]"Faraway So Close", on
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]international connectivity and the North-East region,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]is that, too often,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]transport
[normal] modes plan with almost
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]complete disregard for any other method of travel but theirs.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]The Government'
[normal]s
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]policy for roads, insofar
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]as it can be discerned at all, seems similarly blinkered
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]for
[normal] much of the time. NECTAR takes the view that
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]any improvement to, or changes on, the strategic
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]road
[normal] network should be made to the benefit of as many
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]people, in 
[normal]as many categories (e.g., as an
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]irreducible
[normal] minimum, motorist, cyclist, pedestrian, bus/tram/trolley-bus user), as is possible.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
