[normal]How
[normal] can we improve the reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]Without clarifying who, in this context, "we" are, it is frankly impossible to answer this question
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]directly
[normal]. One
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]might, thinking
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]laterally, suggest that to improve the 'efficiency' of travel on any road
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]it
[normal] is advisable to pursue
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]policies that give strong
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]incentives to motorised road users to change to
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]other
[normal] modes of travel, most likely rail,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]but not ignoring the potential of 
[normal]bus
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]services, insofar as these
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]are
[normal] available on 'strategic' roads.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We in NECTAR point out that the movement of large numbers of people into and out of urban
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]employment
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]centres can only be achieved effectively and efficiently with the use
[normal] of mass transit
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]systems
[normal] - bus, tram, trolleybus, train - singly or in combination. In practice, we see too many cars
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]carrying
[normal] 25% or less of their capacity (the driver)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]clogging up urban roads needlessly, with adverse
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]environmental
[normal] consequence
[normal]s to match. Sadly, the largely-privatised 
[normal]régimes
[normal] under which bus and
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]rail
[normal] systems are now run make a modal change the more difficult - but
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]NECTAR considers that the
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]              
[normal]effort
[normal] needs to be made nonetheless.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal] 
